WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.197
Some changes are physical. The material changes shape,
form, or place, but nothing new is made. Same substance,
new outfit.

2
00:00:10.197 --> 00:00:24.057
Melting ice: physical. Cutting paper: physical. Dissolving
sugar: physical - the sugar spreads out among the water
particles, but it is not rebuilt into anything new.

3
00:00:24.057 --> 00:00:32.576
A chemical change is different. New substances form, with
new properties. Keep that word in mind: new.

4
00:00:32.576 --> 00:00:40.345
Chemists hunt for clues. One clue is a hint, not proof. We
are detectives, not fortune tellers.

5
00:00:40.345 --> 00:00:54.718
Clue one: a gas is made. Fizzing can mean a new gas is
forming. But be careful - boiling water bubbles too, and
that is just water changing state, not a new substance.

6
00:00:54.718 --> 00:01:02.052
Clue two: colour change. If a substance changes colour
during a reaction, something new may be forming.

7
00:01:02.052 --> 00:01:12.690
Clue three: temperature change. Some reactions warm up.
Some cool down. Either way, energy is on the move, and
that is worth noticing.

8
00:01:12.690 --> 00:01:27.628
Clue four: a new solid appears inside a liquid. It might
look cloudy, or like tiny specks drifting down. Chemists
call that solid a precipitate - and it counts as a new

9
00:01:27.628 --> 00:01:37.542
Clue five: light. Burning and some other reactions give
off light. We are reading evidence today, not lighting
flames.

10
00:01:37.542 --> 00:01:55.849
Rusting is a chemical change in slow motion. Iron reacts
with oxygen and water to make rust - a new, crumbly,
orange substance. Paint, oil, or keeping things dry all

11
00:01:55.849 --> 00:02:10.190
Indicators give another kind of evidence. A safe indicator
changes colour in acids or alkalis. What we never do is
taste or sniff unknown liquids. Chemistry has rules

12
00:02:10.190 --> 00:02:24.016
Now compare two changes. Ice melts into liquid water: same
substance, different state. Toast browns: new substances
form, which is why burnt toast does not un-burn when it

13
00:02:24.016 --> 00:02:37.062
Another pair. Salt dissolving can be reversed - evaporate
the water and the salt comes back. Rust is far harder to
reverse, because a brand-new substance now coats the

14
00:02:37.062 --> 00:02:51.063
So keep the checklist: gas, colour, temperature, light,
new solid. Any of them can matter. But the strongest
answer always asks the real question - did a new substance

15
00:02:51.063 --> 00:03:03.337
Here is the deepest idea. In a chemical reaction, atoms
are rearranged. None vanish. None appear from nowhere.
They simply link up in new combinations.

16
00:03:03.337 --> 00:03:15.622
That means mass does not disappear either. In a closed
container, every atom you started with is still there -
even if some are now hiding as an invisible gas.

17
00:03:15.622 --> 00:03:27.494
You do not need balanced equations yet. You need the idea
behind them: the starting substances are reactants, the
ending substances are products, and the same atoms did all

18
00:03:27.494 --> 00:03:40.241
One more warning: some clues show up in physical changes
too. Boiling makes bubbles. Even dissolving can change the
temperature a little. That is why a chemist never trusts

19
00:03:40.241 --> 00:03:53.211
